Hamatu wrote:I know it's a bit unpopular to say, but I feel like realism for realism's sake can also be pretty boring

I know a guy who wrote a ten-page employment agreement for a fictional hypermarket franchise in his lore. Sometimes realism people are on a whole different level. But yeah, I do agree with that point - realism can be a good tool, and taking time to consider realism can be a great way to get interesting ideas, but it isn't uncommon for excessive focus on realism to detract from the more interesting and fun parts of worldbuilding. I feel like it's also often motivated by a sort of realist-elitism, where people assume that "more realistic = better" and try to one-up everyone else in that regard.

I sincerely doubt I could find a wide variety of Middle Eastern/Central Asian anime characters. Very specific, but have you searched up Kaoru Mori's A Bride's Story? The setting is in 19th Century Central Asia.

They even have a neat little map, see?


For me, using animated characters is a no brainer because I unironically consider it less intrusive than using contemporary RL celebrities or some poor bastard from stock photos or out-of-context social media. RL politicans, in contrast, usually feel boring and quick. I as sure as hell wouldn't enjoy my face plastered on some badly-written political story or would-be ERP and I don't think anybody else would either. Even if the ethics of "borrowing" somebody else's work can be called into question and I try my best to draw my own abominations, I'd lose way more sleep if I were using non-consenting people's images...instead of unthinking, unfeeling and non-existent collections of pixels or ink.

And as Resilient Acceleration once said, I think, the good thing about using cartoons/anime is that if they're popular enough, a fanbase churns out a buttload of content to choose from and varied expressions, costumes and situations that can't be repeated by bot profile pics or most RL politicians. I also think that the stylistic variety in anime can provide the means to avoid cutesy or saccharine characters if one actually truly wants to set their mind to it and look beyond the more commercialized or mainstream stuff: Like these for example.

by Kyoki Chudoku Bunkatsu » Mon Apr 12, 2021 12:38 am

So as someone primarily focused on an anime-inspired, FanT nation, I feel somewhat obligated to offer my perspective on that whole debate. Kyoki Chudoku kind of inherently has anime influence in its lifeblood, since the whole original concept of the nation was going wild with all sorts of crazy ideas, many of which were influenced by the fact I was watching a whole bunch of anime at the time and felt like horrifically deconstructing some of the common tropes and archetypes in these things- ok, deconstructing is giving myself too much credit, but you get the idea.

I tend not to make pure MT nations these days. That’s just because I don’t have much to add to them. I am awful, absolutely awful, at making the mundane interesting. So I prefer to throw around more wild concepts, whether they’re inspired by anime or science fiction or the last game I happened to spend a few hours messing around in, just because I’m more passionate about these things in general. FanT offers a lot of flexibility, and realism has never been my focus. My two main aesthetic choices tend to be anime- because it’s a varied visual style that appeals to me personally and happens to fit my random fits of insanity decently well- and Spore abomination, because...well that’s the only way I can design hideous alien life-forms. Realistic art just doesn’t really appeal to me personally. It feels like taking things that already exist and trying to graft them into a world that doesn’t exist, and since nothing I make is really supposed to exist- well, it just doesn’t fit well for me.

Anyway, that’s my incessant rambling on aesthetics.
